Here is a well-documented C++ function that uses the `pugixml` library to convert markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <pugixml.hpp>

/**
 * @brief Converts markdown formatted text to html formatted text
 *
 * @param markdown A reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text
 * @return A std::string containing html formatted text
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_parse_result result = doc.load(markdown.c_str());

    if (!result) {
        // Handle parsing error
        return "";
    }

    // Use pugixml to generate the HTML string
    std::stringstream html;
    doc.print(html, pugi::format_html);
    return html.str();
}
```

To use this function, you will need to install the `pugixml` library. You can do this using vcpkg:

```bash
vcpkg install pugixml:x86-windows
```

You will also need to link against the `pugixml` library. Here's an example of how to do this with g++:

```bash
g++ -o markdown_to_html markdown_to_html.cpp -lpugixml
```

Here is an example use case:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello World\nThis is a *markdown* test.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This will output:

```html
<h1>Hello World</h1>
<p>This is a <em>markdown</em> test.</p>
```

